Shun Coney

Film director Shun Coney praised the excellence and social significance of the documentary. He said, “The documentary is based on years of investigation. Event Organizer Urges the Chinese Government to Respect Human Rights

Event organizer Ms. Suda said, “Organ transplantation requires a high degree of moral and ethical considerations. However, the Chinese government seems to regard the bodies of its citizens as state property and believes that organs are also state property. The U.S. Congress once again introduced the Falun Gong Protection Act
In the last Congress, the U.S. House of Representatives' version of the Falun Gong Protection Act was also introduced by Congressman Perry and passed by the House of Representatives in June 2024. The Senate version was introduced by then-U.S. Republican Senator Marco Rubio of Florida, but it was not considered in time due to the U.S. presidential election.

Diplomacy and human rights are Rubio's areas of expertise in legislation in the U.S. Senate. Now that he has become the U.S. Secretary of State, his colleague Cruz continues his efforts on human rights in China in the U.S. Senate.

Like Rubio, Cruz has been the main spokesperson in the U.S. Senate for condemning the human rights atrocities of the Chinese Communist Party's persecution of religious groups. Last November, Cruz ran for re-election and began his third six-year term in the Senate this year.

Last July, on the 25th anniversary of the persecution of Falun Gong in China, Cruz said in a letter of support to Falun Gong practitioners in Texas, USA: "We have an obligation to speak for those who suffer in China and let the world hear our voices. As the leader of the free world, the United States has a responsibility to defend and promote unimpeded freedom of religious belief. We must publicly condemn the CCP's persecution and hold them accountable. I strongly condemn China's (CCP) treatment of Falun Gong practitioners, and I am proud to stand with you."

In the United States, the persecution of Falun Gong has always been a bipartisan issue. The consensus among Washington DC politicians and American voters that the CCP threatens the national security of the United States has become stronger and stronger. The human rights issues in China, especially the CCP's persecution of Falun Gong, have also received more attention from members of both parties in the United States.

Last July, bipartisan members of the U.S. Senate and House of Representatives expressed support for Falun Gong practitioners' adherence to their beliefs. And Raja Krishnamoorthi, the Democratic chief of the U.S. House of Representatives' Select Committee on Strategic Competition between the United States and the Chinese Communist Party (Select Committee on the CCP), also issued a statement supporting Falun Gong practitioners' peaceful resistance to the persecution and condemning the CCP's persecution.

On Falun Dafa Day last May, bipartisan U.S. lawmakers also congratulated and commended Falun Gong for its contributions to communities across the U.S.

The bill confirms that the CCP has committed the crime of live organ harvesting
In March 2006, The Epoch Times first exposed the CCP's practice of live organ harvesting from prisoners of conscience and the formation of an organ supply chain supported and promoted by the state. Later, David Matas, an international human rights lawyer from Canada, also conducted an independent investigation and came to the same conclusion in July 2006, calling the CCP's crime of live organ harvesting "slow-motion genocide."

The U.S. State Department's annual human rights report, published in May 2012, also first raised the issue of the CCP's live organ harvesting from Falun Gong practitioners. In 2019, the UK's independent "People's Tribunal" (China Tribunal) unanimously determined that prisoners of conscience have been - and continue to be - killed "on a large scale" in China to obtain organs. The tribunal report pointed out that Falun Gong practitioners have been one of the main sources of the CCP's organ supply.

Since then, the fact that the CCP systematically harvested organs from living Falun Gong practitioners has been widely known by Washington DC political circles, especially professionals in human rights diplomacy. The number of organ transplants and the timetable for successful matching mentioned in the "Falun Gong Protection Act" will pave the way for further exposing the details of the CCP's live organ harvesting.

The launch of the "Falun Gong Protection Act" at this time is also of special significance. Currently, the CCP is launching a new round of persecution of Falun Gong around the world, intending to evade international sanctions.

Last December, the leaked documents of the Chinese Ministry of State Security obtained by the US-based human rights monitoring organization "World Organization to Investigate the Persecution of Falun Gong" (WOIPFG, referred to as "Investigation International") showed that the Chinese regime is trying to implement a plan to "eliminate Falun Gong worldwide" by provoking the US government to fight Falun Gong, and to "take all necessary measures" to prevent the US human rights sanctions plan.

At a national online conference held by the Ministry of State Security in May and June last year, senior CCP officials reiterated that they regard Falun Gong as a "potential security threat" in the country and believe that Falun Gong will no longer exist in China without the international support of overseas practitioners.

According to sources from the International Coalition to Investigate the Persecution of Falun Gong, the Chinese Communist Party has conducted multiple fraudulent activities, one of which was specifically aimed at alienating the relationship between the U.S. government and Falun Gong practitioners, spreading rumors such as "the U.S. government has been bought by the Chinese Communist Party and will ban Falun Gong."

Prior to this, the Epoch Times also exclusively broke the news in early December last year that before the 20th National Congress of the Communist Party of China, Party leader Xi Jinping attended a secret meeting of the Political and Legal Affairs Commission, the Public Security Bureau, and the National Security Bureau, accusing them of failing to persecute Falun Gong and determining a new direction: launching a public opinion war and a legal war against Falun Gong overseas. Xi specifically requested that the founder of Falun Gong be attacked for his personality and made this a priority.

Chen Yixin, who attended the meeting as the Secretary-General of the Political and Legal Affairs Commission at the time, later succeeded as the Minister of National Security. In order to pursue his power ambitions, he also actively promoted a new round of attacks on Falun Gong overseas.

As a result, several legal lawsuits against Falun Gong occurred in the United States last year. At the same time, since August last year, the New York Times has also published a number of articles questioning the operation and management of the American Shen Yun Performing Arts Company founded by Falun Gong practitioners, but downplayed the persecution of Falun Gong by the Chinese Communist Party. Even in one article, a Yale University scholar was quoted as saying that there is "no evidence" that the CCP systematically harvests organs from living Falun Gong practitioners.

Despite the CCP's efforts to eliminate information about live organ harvesting and its attempt to get the U.S. government to ban Falun Gong in the United States, American elected leaders are taking further action on this crime with the support of voters. In the coming years, the CCP's crime of live organ harvesting from Falun Gong practitioners may become an important focus of Sino-U.S. relations. ◇

(Epoch Times reporter Eva Fu contributed to this article)

Banned? Says who? Yall really think, on any level, these Chinese factory district direct brokers who only care about duping some guilo round eye out of a buck care if something is 'banned'? Like, even if thats some clever turn of phrase or some shit, the very concept makes literally zero sense. These are brokers, who make their money off of the random shit that falls out the back of a factory district. Factory district. You know how LA has the fabric district with a lot of textile shops? Yeah, not Chinese factory districts. Factory districts are literally an entire industrial district, owned by one company, where plastic injection molding is done in building 5 on floor 3, PCBs are produced in building 23 on floor 6, various components and ICs in building 26, motors in building 34, they ride conveyors to building 12 where they are assembled into whatever circuit they have the parts for. The plastic comes from prototype designs, companies that didnt pay the "dont counterfeit me bro" fee, or .... seriously whatever they can slap together. Ever wonder why there are 5 companies that sell effectively the same device? Yeah, thats why. Oh, and you're ordering this stuff doorstep to doorstep. There is literally NO ONE whos reputation is on the line, much less anyone who is legally obligated to follow consumer protection laws and regulations, between the person taking your money and whatever mildly radioactive, lead painted, ABSOLUTELY NOT THE CORRECT MATERIAL TO GO INTO YOUR BODY, OR SHOULD BE NEAR YOUR KIDS, ticking time bomb fire hazard happens to show up on your door step. 

By the way, dont blame amazon or temu, or banggood, or wish, or whatever..... they're just digital store fronts. They are as minimally invested as its possible to be. They just connect you to the chow hai shilling chinese crap. 

And yet, somehow, someone, 'banned' any of these items? But its a private transaction, and shipping item. Who do yall think is regulating anything that could effect that? 🤣🤣🤣 Fuck man, people are duuuuuuuumb....i guess thats why we're where were at in societies slow crumble, eh? Fuckin dolts.....
